John Edward: linguistic skills are vital for citizens of the world
The independent schools in Scotland have a long history of academic excellence, which has continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding results in the examinations, which is further enhanced by individual and collective successes in sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 pupils in Scotland, these centres, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS, for its acronym in English), strive to deliver the best possible service to pupils and parents.
Independent schools are designed to prepare their pupils for further education, for the career they choose and for the place they occupy in the world.
As a modern language, popular and in demand in the centres, modern languages continue to be a subject of choice for students.
As Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, that goes to his head. If you talk to him in his native language, that goes to his heart."
If you speak to them in their language, you reach their heart.
This is a powerful reminder that, if one wishes to establish relations and build trust with people from other countries, one cannot rely solely on English.
If we look at the recent results of the examinations, we can see that languages are at the top of the ranking tables, with the highest pass rates in independent schools.
Overall, 68 per cent of students who studied foreign languages received an A, the highest grade.
The data, collected from the 74 centres that make up the SCIS, showed that 72 % of students achieved an A in Mandarin, while 72 % of students studying German, French and Spanish also achieved an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a fundamental skill that will be needed by children and young people in the future without doubt.
Languages are now considered on a par with the CTIM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and everywhere else.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 found that 17 per cent of employers cited language skills as a barrier to filling jobs.
Language skills are therefore becoming increasingly indispensable for preparing young people for their future careers.
The potential for language skills in the workplace is increasing, and these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career path someone chooses, if he or she has learned a second language, he or she will have a real advantage in the future because of this, which will last a lifetime.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically give that person an advantage over the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of over 4,000 adults in the United Kingdom in 2013, 75 per cent of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and 15 per cent spoke only French.
For this reason, investing in language education is important for today &apos; s children.
If they know several languages, especially those of developing economies, children will be better equipped to have better opportunities for quality employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centres will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach the more important languages for the United Kingdom by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the child's interests, independent schools will always offer a choice of languages taught by specialist staff.
Independent schools in Scotland are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children for life and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever their future holds.
In a global business environment, languages remain vital to the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages must be considered "competencies for international communication."
Independent schools in Scotland will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people.
Well, that is that.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Independent Schools Council.
