However, a sniper killed him four days later and he never knew that he had been awarded the highest military honour in Britain.
On Saturday, his two grandchildren found a commemorative stone in a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
One of them, Michael Vann, said that it was "a particularly symbolic find" that the stone was discovered exactly 100 years after the battle that earned his grandfather the medal.
According to the London Gazette, on 29 September 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Vann led his battalion through the Saint-Quentin Canal "through a dense fog and under intense machine-gun and artillery fire."
He then ran the line to the enemy line and, with the "greatest bravery," advanced the line to a single trench and knocked out three of the enemy with one hand.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on 4 October 1918, just one month after the war ended.
Michael Vann, 72, said that his grandfather &apos; s actions were &quot; so great that I will never be able to reach his level, but they were very instructive.
He and his brother, Dr. James Vann, also laid a wreath after the parade, which was attended by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said it was a privilege for him to be part of the parade and added that the value of a true hero was evident when he was shown such a strong show of support.
