The new German warship, postponed again
The new German Navy frigate was supposed to be commissioned in 2014 to replace the old Cold War-era ships, but it will not be commissioned until at least next year due to faulty systems and the increasing cost of the project, local media reported.
The delivery of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the lead ship of the new Baden-Württemberg-class frigates, has now been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to a report in the German newspaper Die Zeit.
The ship was supposed to join the Navy in 2014, but problems that arose after the delivery of the ship delayed the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Württemberg-class ships requested by the Navy in 2007 will replace the old Bremen-class frigates.
We know that it will include a powerful cannon, a set of anti-aircraft and anti-missile missiles, as well as some technologies of invisibility, such as radar, infrared and acoustic signatures that are very small.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods, allowing deployment away from home ports for up to two years.
However, the delays have meant that the innovative ships (which were supposed to allow Germany to project its power into the oceans) will be already out of date by the time they start service, as Die Zeit points out.
The unfortunate F125 frigate was officially decommissioned last year, when the German Navy officially rejected the ship and returned it to the Blohm &amp; Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time that a ship had been returned to a shipyard after delivery.
The reasons for the return were not known, but German media cited a number of "software and hardware defects" that left the ship practically useless if sent on a combat mission.
The software deficiencies were particularly important, as the Baden-Württemberg-class ships will be operated by a crew of 120 sailors: half the crew of the old Bremen-class frigates.
It was also found that the ship is overweight, which reduces its performance and limits the Navy &apos; s ability to add future upgrades.
It is believed that the "Rheinland-Pfalz" of 7000 tons is twice as heavy as other similar ships used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to the defective hardware, the cost of the entire project, including the training of the crew, has also been a problem.
It is now estimated at EUR 3.1 billion (USD 4.2 billion), up from the initial EUR 2.2 billion.
The problems associated with the new frigates are of particular relevance in the light of recent warnings about the reduction in the naval power of Germany.
At the beginning of this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, chairman of the German parliament's defence committee, acknowledged that the Navy was "losing ships capable of deploying."
The official said that the problem has been getting worse over time, because old ships have been decommissioned but not replaced.
He regretted that none of the Baden-Württemberg-class frigates had been able to join the Navy.
The National Trust spies on the secret lives of bats
This new research, carried out in a Scottish Highlands area, is attempting to discover how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
All that is learned will shed more light on the behaviour of the only flying mammals and help to guide future conservation efforts.
The National Trust for Scotland will continue to monitor common and soprano pipistrelle, as well as Daubenton &apos; s bat and brown long-eared bats in the Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special bat detectors will be placed at strategic locations on the property to monitor bat activity during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using hand-held detectors.
The experts will analyse the sounds recorded in the recordings to determine the frequency of the calls of the bats and the species that make them.
A report and map of the habitat will then be produced to provide a detailed picture of the environment and its behaviour.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation adviser for NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of grasslands and how to maintain forests for bats and other associated species.
The populations of bats in Scotland and the United Kingdom have declined considerably in the last century.
They are under threat from construction and development that affects their nests and habitat.
Wind turbines and electrical cabling can also pose a risk to them, as can insecticides and other chemical treatments of construction materials or attacks by domestic cats.
Mosquitoes are not actually blind.
Unless they are nocturnal hunters, their ears are more useful than their eyes in finding their prey.
They use a sophisticated technique of ecolocation to locate ants and obstacles on their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, takes the subject of bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts who regularly conduct surveys, nest inspections and, on occasion, rescue operations.
The organization has even opened Scotland &apos; s first and only bat reserve at Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland &apos; s ten bat species.
The property manager, David Thompson, says it is the ideal territory for them.
Here at Threave, we have a fantastic area for bats," he said.
We have old buildings, many veteran trees and the right habitat.
However, there is still much to be learned about bats, and the work we do here and at other properties will help us to better understand what they need to thrive."
It emphasizes the importance of checking for bats before carrying out maintenance work on properties, as a colony of bats can be destroyed unintentionally and 400 females and young can be killed, which would wipe out an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass, or destroy their colonies.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to help.
He said: "We still have much to learn about bats and many other species about which we know little about their populations."
