Foreigners will pay a higher stamp duty when buying property in the United Kingdom.
Foreigners will be subject to a higher stamp duty when they buy property in the United Kingdom and the extra money raised will be used to house the homeless, according to the new plans of the Conservatives.
The change will neutralize the success of Corbyn's offensive to attract younger voters
The increase in the land transfer tax will be imposed on those persons who are not paying taxes in the United Kingdom.
The Treasury expects to raise up to £120 million a year for the homeless.
The additional money raised from the increase in stamp duty on foreign buyers of property in the United Kingdom will be used to help the homeless, Theresa May said today.
The measure is seen as an attempt to neutralize the success that Jeremy Corbyn is having with his promises of providing more affordable housing to attract younger voters and to harass those with higher incomes.
The increase in the land transfer tax will be levied on individuals and companies who do not pay taxes in the United Kingdom and that money will be used to incentivize government policy to combat street begging.
The levy, which is an additional charge on the current transfer tax, including the increase in levels introduced two years ago on second-hand homes and the "buy-to-let" system, could reach up to 3 per cent.
The Treasury expects to raise up to £120 million a year with this change.
It is estimated that 13 per cent of new build properties in London are bought by people who do not live in the United Kingdom, which is causing house prices to rise and making it difficult for first-time buyers to get on the housing ladder.
Many of the country &apos; s wealthiest areas (especially in the capital) have become &quot; ghost towns &quot; due to the large number of foreign buyers who spend most of their time outside the country.
The new policy comes just weeks after Boris Johnson called for a reduction in stamp duty to help young people buy their first home.
