Red tide update: Red tide concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The new report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission (FFWC) shows a general decrease in red tide concentrations in the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, irregular bloom conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a reduction in concentrations.
The red tide bloom extends approximately 130 miles along the coast from Pinellas County to Lee County.
Irregular parcels can be found as far as 10 miles inland from the coast of Hillsborough County, but fewer than last week.
Red tides have also been detected in Pasco County.
During the past week, medium-sized gatherings have been reported in Pinellas County and along its coast, medium-sized gatherings along the coast of Hillsborough County, medium-sized gatherings of bottom dwellers along the coast of Manatee County, medium-sized gatherings of bottom dwellers along the coast of Sarasota County and its coast, medium-sized gatherings of bottom dwellers along the coast of Charlotte County, medium-sized gatherings of bottom dwellers along the coast of Lee County and its coast, and medium-sized gatherings of bottom dwellers along the coast of Collier County.
Reports of respiratory irritation continue in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
There have been no reports of respiratory irritation in the northwestern part of Florida during the past week.
